Sound Waves

Â» Describing Sound

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Longitudinal waves
  • Vacuum

Sound waves are produced by vibrating sources. They are longitudinal waves, which means a medium is needed for them to travel.

  • In a vacuum, where there are no molecules, sound cannot travel.
  • When sound waves encounter a solid, the vibrations are transferred to the solid.
  • For ðŸ“˜ example, excessive vibration from sound waves can cause a glass to shatter.

Â» Representing Longitudinal Waves

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Longitudinal waves
  • Longitudinal wave

Longitudinal waves are typically shown as a series of parallel lines.

  • Compressions: Areas where the lines are close together.
  • Rarefactions: Areas where the lines are spread apart.

[Diagram: A longitudinal wave showing the direction of vibration parallel to the direction of energy transfer. The diagram labels areas of compression (where wave lines are close together) and rarefactions (where wave lines are spread apart).]

Â» Compression & Rarefaction (Extended Tier Only)

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Longitudinal waves
  • Compressions

Longitudinal waves are made up of compressions and rarefactions:

  • A compression is a region of higher density where molecules are bunched together.
  • A rarefaction is a region of lower density where molecules are spread out.

[Diagram: A visual representation of a sound wave with labeled compressions and rarefactions, showing pressure variations.]

These pressure changes cause the surface of a solid to vibrate when a sound wave hits it. Therefore, sound is considered a pressure wave.

[Diagram: This image shows how sound waves in the air, consisting of rarefactions (low pressure) and compressions (high pressure), strike a solid surface, causing it to vibrate.]

Examiner Tip: When describing compressions and rarefactions, use scientific terms like "regions of high and low density" instead of vague phrases like "bunched up" or "far apart".

Measuring the Speed of Sound

Â» Speed of Sound in Different Media

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Speed of sound

The speed of sound varies depending on the medium and its temperature. In air, it is typically between 330-350 m/s.

(Extended Tier Only)

  • Sound travels fastest in solids (around 5000 m/s).
  • It travels slower in liquids (around 1500 m/s).
  • It travels slowest in gases.

Â» Experiment 1: Measuring Speed of Sound Between Two Points

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Speed of sound

Method

[Diagram: An illustration of the ðŸ”¬ experiment setup. One person is shown clapping two wooden blocks together, while another person, standing 100m or more away, holds a stopwatch, ready to time the sound.]

  1. Measure a distance of 100 m between two people using a trundle wheel.
  2. One person bangs two wooden blocks together to create a sound.
  3. The second person starts a stopwatch upon seeing the blocks hit and stops it upon hearing the sound.
  4. Repeat this several times and calculate an average time.
  5. Repeat for different distances (e.g., 120 m, 140 m, etc.).

Analysis

The speed of sound is calculated using the formula: average speed = distance / time. The expected result is around 340 m/s.

Â» Experiment 2: Measuring Speed of Sound with an Oscilloscope

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Oscilloscope
  • Microphone
  • Speed of sound

Method

[Diagram: Setup for the second ðŸ”¬ experiment. Two microphones are placed a few metres apart and connected to an oscilloscope. A clap is made next to the first microphone.]

  1. Connect two microphones to an oscilloscope, placing them about 2 m apart.
  2. Set the oscilloscope to trigger on the first sound detected.
  3. Make a loud clap next to the first microphone.
  4. Use the oscilloscope to find the time difference between the sound arriving at each microphone.
  5. Repeat for various distances.

Analysis

The speed of sound is calculated using the same formula: average speed = distance / time.

Â» Evaluating the Experiments

Systematic Errors

In ðŸ”¬ Experiment 2, ensure the time base scale on the oscilloscope is read correctly, as it is often in milliseconds.

Random Errors

In Experiment 1, human reaction time is the main source of error. To minimize this, take repeat readings, calculate an average, and use the largest possible distance.

Examiner Tip: ðŸ”¬ Experiment 2 is more accurate due to automatic timing. Experiment 1 is less accurate because the short time interval makes human reaction error more significant. Suggesting improvements like increasing the distance can show a deeper understanding.

Effects of Sound Waves

Â» Pitch & Loudness

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Frequency
  • Amplitude
  • The pitch of a sound is related to its frequency. High pitch means high frequency.
  • The loudness (volume) of a sound is related to its amplitude. High volume means large amplitude.

[Diagram: Four oscilloscope traces demonstrating the relationship between pitch, volume, frequency, and amplitude.]

Â» Echoes

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Echo

An echo is the reflection of a sound wave off a hard surface.

[Diagram: A person stands at least 50m from a wall and claps. The sound wave travels to the wall and reflects back to the person as an echo.]

The distance to the reflecting surface can be calculated with the formula: distance = 0.5 * speed * time, where 'time' is the total time for the sound to travel to the surface and back.

Ultrasound

The range of human hearing is approximately 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz (20 kHz). Sound with a frequency higher than 20 kHz is defined as ultrasound.

[Diagram: A frequency spectrum showing that frequencies below 20 Hz are infrasound, frequencies between 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz are in the range of human hearing, and frequencies above 20,000 Hz are ultrasound.]

Â» Uses of Ultrasound (Extended Tier Only)

  • Non-destructive testing of materials.
  • Medical scanning of soft tissues.
  • Sonar for calculating depth or distance.

Â» How Ultrasound Works

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Frequency
  • Oscilloscope
  • Echoes
  • Echo

Ultrasound transducers emit and receive high-frequency sound waves. When these waves hit a boundary between two different media, some are reflected and some are transmitted. The time taken for the reflected waves to return is used to calculate the distance to the boundary.

[Diagram: An illustration of how depth is measured. An emitted sound wave travels down to a boundary, reflects off it, and the reflected wave travels back up to a receiver.]

The formula is: depth = 0.5 * speed * time.

Ultrasound in Material Testing

Ultrasound can detect internal cracks in metal objects. A crack will reflect the wave back sooner than the far end of the object. An oscilloscope displays these reflections as pulses, allowing engineers to identify flaws.

[Diagram: A setup for testing a steel bolt, with an oscilloscope trace showing pulses from the bolt head, an internal crack, and the end of the bolt.]

Ultrasound in Medicine

Used to create images of a foetus, organs, and other internal structures. It's considered non-invasive and harmless. The process involves a transducer sending pulses into the body and detecting the echoes that reflect off boundaries between tissues.

[Diagram: The 4-step process of medical ultrasound, resulting in an image of a baby in the womb.]

Sonar

Echo sounding uses ultrasound to measure water depth or detect underwater objects. A sound wave is sent from a ship, reflects off the seabed, and the return time is used to calculate the depth.

[Diagram: A boat on the surface of the water uses echo sounding to determine the water depth where a submarine is located.]

Â» Worked Example

Plain NotesExperimentExam TipExample
  • Speed of sound
  • Oscilloscope

A high-frequency sound wave is used to check for cracks in a steel bolt. The speed of sound in steel is 6000 m/s. An oscilloscope trace shows a reflection from a crack. Each division on the time axis represents 0.000002 s, and the reflection appears at the 5th division. Calculate the distance to the crack in cm.

[Diagram: An oscilloscope trace showing a pulse detected at the 5th division, where each division represents 0.000002 s.]

  1. List known quantities:
    Speed (v) = 6000 m/s
    Time (t) = 5 divisions * 0.000002 s/division = 0.00001 s
  2. Equation: distance = speed * time
  3. Calculate total distance:
    Total distance = 6000 m/s * 0.00001 s = 0.06 m
  4. Calculate distance to crack (one way):
    Distance to crack = 0.06 m / 2 = 0.03 m
  5. Convert to cm:
    Distance to crack = 3 cm
